---
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/Nav.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const title = "Why AI Coding Agents Need a Health App — Harness Health";
const description =
  "A product essay on why AI coding agents need longitudinal health reporting instead of only per-session chat history.";
---

<SiteLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Nav />
  <main id="main">
    <article class="article-page">
      <header class="article-hero">
        <div class="container section-narrow">
          <span class="eyebrow">Blog / Product note</span>
          <h1>Why AI coding agents need a health app.</h1>
          <p class="lead">
            The useful question is not “was this one answer good?” It is “is
            the way I work with this harness getting healthier?”
          </p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="container article-grid">
        <aside class="article-aside card">
          <img
            src="/story-mobile-review.png"
            alt=""
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
            class="aside-image"
          />
          <span class="mono">Thesis</span>
          <strong>Agent quality is longitudinal.</strong>
          <p>Repeated patterns matter more than isolated wins or misses.</p>
        </aside>

        <div class="article-body">
          <p>
            AI coding tools already generate plenty of output. What they often
            lack is reflection. A harness can ship a patch, run tools, and
            explain itself, but still repeat the same avoidable mistake
            tomorrow because no system turned today’s friction into guidance.
          </p>

          <h2>Health is a trend, not a transcript</h2>
          <p>
            A single transcript is useful for debugging a moment. Health
            reporting is useful for changing a habit. Harness Health looks
            across sessions for metrics and repeated shapes: cost per accepted
            change, correction rate, re-asks, failed tools, and repo-specific
            gaps.
          </p>

          <h2>Communication should be calm</h2>
          <p>
            The user should not wake up to a dense analytics dashboard. The
            report should feel closer to a daily readiness check: one important
            thing, a few supporting vitals, and suggested improvements that can
            be accepted or ignored.
          </p>

          <h2>The goal is better collaboration</h2>
          <p>
            The best recommendations help both sides. The agent gets clearer
            project memory and validation paths. The user spends less time
            repeating instructions. The next report checks whether the change
            actually helped.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</SiteLayout>
